<sect1 id="index_1intro_sec">
<title>Introduction</title>
<para>AnalysisG is a comprehensive framework designed for graph-based analysis in high-energy physics (HEP). It provides a flexible and extensible architecture for processing physics event data, constructing graph representations, applying machine learning models, and evaluating analysis results.</para>
<para>The framework is built with modern C++ and integrates with PyTorch for machine learning capabilities, making it suitable for both traditional physics analysis and cutting-edge ML-based approaches.</para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="index_1architecture_sec">
<title>Architecture Overview</title>
<para>The AnalysisG framework is organized into several main components:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para><bold>Core Module</bold> (<ref refid="group__core__group" kindref="compound">Core Module</ref>): Contains the foundational C++ implementations for graph structures, nodes, and edges that form the basis of the graph-based analysis approach.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para><bold>Modules</bold> (<ref refid="group__modules__group" kindref="compound">Modules</ref>): Contains specialized modules that extend the framework&apos;s functionality, including event processing, graph building, model training, and metrics evaluation.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para><bold>CUDA Acceleration</bold> (<ref refid="group__cuda__group" kindref="compound">CUDA Accelerated Computing</ref>): GPU-accelerated physics computations and tensor operations for high-performance analysis.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para><bold>Python Bindings</bold> (<ref refid="group__cython__group" kindref="compound">Cython Python Bindings</ref>): Cython-based Python interface for seamless integration with Python workflows and Jupyter notebooks.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para><bold>Pre-built Templates</bold> (<ref refid="group__prebuilt__group" kindref="compound">Pre-built Templates</ref>): Ready-to-use event, graph, model, and selection templates for common HEP analysis tasks.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="index_1getting_started">
<title>Getting Started</title>
<para>To begin using AnalysisG, you&apos;ll typically:</para>
<para><orderedlist>
<listitem><para>Define your event data structure by subclassing <ref refid="classevent__template" kindref="compound">event_template</ref></para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Create particle representations using <ref refid="classparticle__template" kindref="compound">particle_template</ref></para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Build graph structures with <ref refid="classgraph__template" kindref="compound">graph_template</ref></para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Apply selections using <ref refid="classselection__template" kindref="compound">selection_template</ref></para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Train or apply models using <ref refid="classmodel__template" kindref="compound">model_template</ref></para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Evaluate results with <ref refid="classmetric__template" kindref="compound">metric_template</ref></para>
</listitem></orderedlist>
</para>
<para>See <ref refid="getting_started_page" kindref="compound">Getting Started with AnalysisG</ref> for a detailed guide.</para>
</sect1>
